<p>HUMAN RIGHTS COUNCIL 
Sixth session 
Agenda item 10 
</p>
<p><b>TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE AND CAPACITY-BUILDING 
</b></p>
<p><b>Austria</b>*<b>, Belgium</b>*<b>, Bulgaria</b>*<b>, Cyprus</b>*<b>, Czech Republic</b>*<b>, Denmark</b>*<b>, Estonia</b>*<b>, 
Finland</b>*<b>, France, Germany, Greece</b>*<b>, Hungary</b>*<b>, Ireland</b>*<b>, Italy, Latvia</b>*<b>, 
Lithuania</b>*<b>, Luxembourg</b>*<b>, Malta</b>*<b>, Netherlands, Poland</b>*<b>, Portugal</b>*<b>, Romania, 
Slovakia</b>*<b>, Slovenia, Spain</b>*<b>, Sweden</b>*<b> and United Kingdom of Great Britain 
                                  and Northern Ireland:  draft resolution 
</b></p>
<p><b>6/&#8230; Mandate of the Special Rapporteur on the 
situation of human rights in the Sudan 
</b></p>
<p><i> The Human Rights Council</i>, 
</p>
<p> <i>Guided</i> by the principles and objectives of the Charter of the United Nations, the 
Universal Declaration of Human Rights and the International Covenants on Human Rights, 
</p>
<p> <i>Reaffirming </i>that all Member States have an obligation to promote and protect 
human rights and fundamental freedoms as stated in the Charter of the United Nations, the 
Universal Declaration of Human Rights, the International Covenants on Human Rights and 
other applicable human rights instruments, 
</p>
<p>                                                 
</p>
<p>*  Non-member States of the Human Rights Council. </p>

 <p></p>
<p><i> Recalling </i>General Assembly resolution 60/251 of 15 March 2006, 
</p>
<p><i> Recalling also </i>its resolutions 5/1 &#8220;Institution-building of the United Nations 
Human Rights Council&#8221; and 5/2 &#8220;Code of Conduct for Special Procedures mandate-holders of 
the Human Rights Council&#8221; of 18 June 2007, and stressing that the mandate-holder shall 
discharge his/her duties in accordance with those resolutions and the annexes thereto, 
</p>
<p><i> Having conducted </i>an assessment of the mandate of the Special Rapporteur in the form of 
an interactive dialogue during its present session, in accordance with its resolution 5/1, 
</p>
<p> <i>Reaffirming </i>Commission on Human Rights resolution 2005/82 of 21 April 2005, 
</p>
<p> <i>Bearing in mind</i> the report on the situation of human rights in all regions of the Sudan 
submitted by the Special Rapporteur (A/62/354) and urging the implementation of the 
recommendations contained therein, 
</p>
<p><i> Welcoming</i> the report submitted by the Group of Experts on the situation of human rights 
in Darfur (A/HRC/6/19) and urging the implementation of the recommendations contained 
therein, 
</p>
<p><i> Deeply concerned</i> at the situation of human rights throughout the Sudan, notably, at the 
slow pace of implementation of the Comprehensive Peace Agreement and the gross violations of 
human rights that continue to be perpetrated in the Darfur region, 
</p>
<p> <i>Acknowledging </i>the constructive cooperation of the Government of the Sudan with the 
Council and its mechanisms, 
</p>
<p> 1. <i>Decides </i>to extend for one year the mandate of the Special Rapporteur on the 
situation of human rights in the Sudan and requests the Special Rapporteur: 
</p>
<p> (<i>a</i>) To monitor the situation of human rights in the Sudan; 
</p>
<p> (<i>b</i>) To foster the effectiveness of international technical and financial support for 
the Sudan in the field of human rights;  </p>

 <p></p>
<p> (<i>c</i>) To submit to the Council a full annual report before the end of 2008, as well as all 
outstanding reports, in accordance with its annual programme of work; 
</p>
<p> 2. <i>Urges</i> the Government of the Sudan to continue cooperating fully with the 
Special Rapporteur and to respond favourably to her requests to visit the Sudan and to provide 
her with all necessary information so as to enable her to fulfil her<b> </b>mandate even more 
effectively; 
</p>
<p> 3. <i>Calls upon</i> the Secretary-General to provide the Special Rapporteur with all 
necessary assistance to enable her to discharge her mandate fully; 
</p>
<p> 4. <i>Invites</i> relevant United Nations bodies and agencies, including the Office of the 
United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights, to continue providing support and 
technical assistance to the Sudan in the field of human rights and calls upon donors to also 
continue providing financial and technical assistance for the improvement of the human rights 
situation in the Sudan. 
</p>
